{
  "answer": "**Several ancient Indic legal texts (Smṛtis or Dharmashāstras) in the corpus treat written documents (*lekhyas* or *patras*) explicitly as a primary evidentiary medium in judicial proceedings, alongside witnesses and possession. These are classified as one of the three core forms of human proof (*pramāṇas*), used to resolve disputes over debts, property, contracts, and more. Divine ordeals or inference serve as supplements when documents, witnesses, or possession are inconclusive.[^1][^2][^3][^4]**\n\n**Key works include:**\n\n- **Bṛhaspati Smṛti** (*unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070*): Dedicates sections to the characteristics, validity, and examination of documents (e.g., including date, place, parties, seals, and signatures), their role in proof, and when they supersede other evidence. Documents must be proven authentic via witnesses or reasoning.[^5][^6]\n  \n- **Kātyāyana Smṛti** (*unknown-katyayana-smrti-1e06d2*): Lists documents as the first of three evidences (*pramāṇas*), equal in strength to witnesses and possession. The king decides cases via documents, reason, or ordeal; rules cover document defects and their precedence.[^7][^8]\n\n**Related works likely covering similar ground** (based on genre and search hits for evidentiary concepts, though not exhaustively verified here): *Nārada Smṛti* (*unknown-naradasmrti-7650d2*), *Yājñavalkya Smṛti* (*unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6*), *Manusmṛti* (*unknown-manusmrti-347b76*), *Aṅgirasa Smṛti* (*unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1*), *Paraśara Smṛti* (*unknown-parasara-smrti-2259be*), *Viṣṇu Smṛti* (*unknown-visnu-smrti-27f0d8*), and *Yama Smṛti* (*unknown-yama-smrti-552f8d*). These are all ancient Indic law texts emphasizing procedural law (*vyavahāra*), where documents feature prominently.\n\nNo other works (e.g., Charles Comte's *Traité de Législation* or *Traité de la Propriété*, which distinguish \"written laws\" from unwritten customs) discuss writing specifically as an evidentiary tool in legal contexts.\n\n[^1]: Bṛhaspati Smṛti, Ch. 1, [para. p-510297](/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-510297).  \n[^2]: Bṛhaspati Smṛti, Ch. 1, [para. p-c9cb41](/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-c9cb41).  \n[^3]: Kātyāyana Smṛti, Ch. 24, [para. p-b4ce2a](/works/unknown-katyayana-smrti-1e06d2/24/translation/#p-b4ce2a).  \n[^4]: Kātyāyana Smṛti, Ch. 24, [para. p-19695f](/works/unknown-katyayana-smrti-1e06d2/24/translation/#p-19695f).  \n[^5]: Bṛhaspati Smṛti, Ch. 1, [para. p-bbce9d](/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-bbce9d).  \n[^6]: Bṛhaspati Smṛti, Ch. 1, [para. p-82339c](/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-82339c).  \n[^7]: Kātyāyana Smṛti, Ch. 24, [para. p-5310b5](/works/unknown-katyayana-smrti-1e06d2/24/translation/#p-5310b5).  \n[^8]: Kātyāyana Smṛti, Ch. 27, [para. p-08f972](/works/unknown-katyayana-smrti-1e06d2/27/translation/#p-08f972).",
